"\n## Problems\nLet $x$, $y$ and $z$ all exceed $1$ and let $w$ be a positive number such that $\\log_x w = 24$, $\\log_y w = 40$ and $\\log_{xyz} w = 12$. Find $\\log_z w$. Show that it is 060.\n\n## Informal proof\nThe [[logarithm]]ic notation doesn't tell us much, so we'll first convert everything to the equivalent exponential forms.\n\n$x^{24}=w$, $y^{40}=w$, and $(xyz)^{12}=w$. If we now convert everything to a power of $120$, it will be easy to isolate $z$ and $w$.\n\n$x^{120}=w^5$, $y^{120}=w^3$, and $(xyz)^{120}=w^{10}$.\n\nWith some substitution, we get $w^5w^3z^{120}=w^{10}$ and $\\log_zw=060$.\n\n## Formal statement\n```isabelle\ntheorem aime_1983_p1:\n  fixes x y z w :: nat\n  assumes ht : \"1 < x \\<and> 1 < y \\<and> 1 < z\"\n    and hw : \"0 \\<le> w\"\n    and h0 : \"ln w / ln x = 24\"\n    and h1 : \"ln w / ln y = 40\"\n    and h2 : \"ln w / ln (x * y * z) = 12\"\n  shows \"ln w / ln z = 60\"\n```\n\n## Structured informal proof\nStep 1: Convert the logarithmic equations to exponential form:\n  - $x^{24} = w$\n  - $y^{40} = w$\n  - $(xyz)^{12} = w$\n\nStep 2: Raise each equation to the power of 5 to make the exponents comparable:\n  - $x^{120} = w^5$\n  - $y^{120} = w^3$\n  - $(xyz)^{120} = w^{10}$\n\nStep 3: Substitute the expressions for $x^{120}$ and $y^{120}$ into the equation for $(xyz)^{120}$:\n  - $w^5 \\cdot w^3 \\cdot z^{120} = w^{10}$\n\nStep 4: Simplify the equation to isolate $z^{120}$:\n  - $z^{120} = w^{2}$\n\nStep 5: Convert back to logarithmic form to find $\\log_z w$:\n  - $\\log_z w = 60$\n\n## Lemmas\n### Lemma 1\nA lemma showing that if $a = b^c$, then $\\log_b a = c$ would be useful in converting between exponential and logarithmic forms.\n\n### Code 1\n```isabelle\nlemma log_exponential_conversion:\n  fixes a b c :: real\n  assumes \"a = b^c\"\n  shows \"ln a / ln b = c\"\n  by (simp add: assms)\n```\n\n### Lemma 2\nA lemma showing that if $a^m = b^n$, then $a^{km} = b^{kn}$ for any positive integer $k$ would be useful in raising the equations to comparable powers.\n\n### Code 2\n```isabelle\nlemma power_equality:\n  fixes a b m n k :: nat\n  assumes \"a^m = b^n\"\n  shows \"a^(k*m) = b^(k*n)\"\n  by (simp add: assms)\n```\n\n### Lemma 3\nA lemma showing that if $a \\cdot b = c$, then $\\log_d a + \\log_d b = \\log_d c$ for any positive real numbers $a$, $b$, $c$, and $d$ would be useful in combining the logarithmic equations.\n\n### Code 3\n```isabelle\nlemma log_product:\n  fixes a b c d :: real\n  assumes \"a * b = c\"\n  shows \"ln a / ln d + ln b / ln d = ln c / ln d\"\n  by (simp add: assms)\n```\n\nThese lemmas and the structured proof should help in formalizing the given problem in Isabelle."